Wrap mode testing plan
======================

Basic insert wrap
-----------------
- Type into a paragraph until a line overflows — cursor should stay put, text wraps right
- Type in the middle of a line (not at end) — same guarantee
- Type where the only space is before the cursor — no wrap should happen, line goes over-long
- Type a very long word with no spaces — same, line stays over-long until M-q

Basic delete pull-up
--------------------
- Delete chars from the front of a line — next line's first word should flow up
- Delete enough to absorb multiple words — should keep pulling until line is full
- Delete until a continuation line empties entirely — that line should disappear cleanly
- Delete at position 0 (backspace at BOL) — joins with previous line, then wrap_delete runs

Cascade in both directions
--------------------------
- A paragraph with 4+ soft lines: insert in line 1 and verify lines 2, 3, 4 reflow consistently
- Delete in line 1 and verify that words flow up through all subsequent lines
- Delete enough to collapse multiple continuation lines into one

L_SNL flag integrity (the ldelnewline fix)
------------------------------------------
- C-D at the end of a soft-wrapped line (deletes the soft newline, joining with continuation)
  — result should have correct L_SNL
- Backspace at position 0 of a continuation line — same
- After join, further typing or deletion should still trigger wrap correctly

Interaction with M-q / M-Q
---------------------------
- Type sloppily (multiple spaces, uneven lines), then M-q — should fully reflow
- M-Q on a buffer with mixed wrap/non-wrap paragraphs
- M-q after a series of inserts and deletes — should normalize any over-long lines
- M-Q on a file opened with 'me -w <file>' after deletions — should not crash (fillbuf
  dangling pointer fix)

Edge cases
----------
- Single-word paragraph that overflows rmarg (unbreakable) — should not crash or corrupt
- Paragraph at end of buffer with no trailing blank line
- Wrap with a non-zero left margin (lmarg set)
- Kill/yank (C-w / C-y) within a wrapped paragraph — then verify wrap state is consistent

File save/reload
----------------
- Write a wrapped buffer, reload it — soft newlines should be stored as spaces and reload
  as one long line (or vice versa depending on how file.c handles L_SNL on read)
